## 4. Data Release Schedules (Official)

Each data source has a fixed, predictable release schedule. The dashboard should know these and use them to drive all refresh logic — don't fetch early, don't fetch repeatedly, just wait for the right window.

| Series | Release Day | Release Time | Frequency | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Fed Balance Sheet (WALCL) | **Thursday** | **4:30 PM ET** | Weekly | Covers prior Wednesday; shifts to Friday on US federal holidays |
| US M2 (M2SL / H.6) | **Tuesday** | **1:00 PM ET** | Weekly | Weekly data; FRED monthly series `M2SL` updates same day |
| ECB Balance Sheet (ECBASSETSW) | **Tuesday** | ~**10:00 AM CET** | Weekly | Covers prior Friday's balance |
| Bank of Japan Assets | ~20th–25th | varies | Monthly | ~3–4 weeks after reference month |
| China M2 (PBoC) | ~10th–15th | varies | Monthly | ~2 weeks after reference month |
| Australia M2 (RBA) | Last biz day of month+1 | varies | Monthly | ~5–6 week lag is normal; note in UI |

**Key insight:** The two most important series for the global liquidity story — the Fed and ECB balance sheets — are weekly and released on **Thursday and Tuesday** respectively. This means in any given week, you have fresh data by Thursday evening. The monthly series (BOJ, China, Australia) don't change between releases, so re-fetching them more than once a month is pointless.

