## 11. Data Freshness & FRED Accuracy Notes

| Source | Release Day/Time | Data Lag | FRED vs Primary Source |
|---|---|---|---|
| Fed Balance Sheet (WALCL) | **Thu 4:30 PM ET** | ~1 day (covers prior Wed) | FRED = primary source, no lag |
| US M2 (M2SL) | **Tue 1:00 PM ET** | ~1 week | FRED = primary source, no lag |
| ECB Balance Sheet (ECBASSETSW) | **Tue ~10:00 AM CET** | ~4 days (covers prior Fri) | FRED lags ECB Data Portal by ~1 day |
| BOJ Assets (JPNASSETS) | ~20th–25th of month | ~3–4 weeks | FRED lags BOJ by ~2 days |
| China M2 | ~10th–15th of month | ~2 weeks | FRED lags PBOC by ~2 days |
| Australia M2 | ~Last biz day of month+1 | ~5–6 weeks | FRED lags RBA by ~1 day |
| Bitcoin (CoinGecko) | Real-time | Minutes | CoinGecko is primary |
| S&P 500 / NDQ | Real-time | Minutes | Yahoo Finance is primary |

**On FRED being the best source:** Yes, for this dashboard. FRED is the primary publisher for all US data (there is no closer source). For international data (ECB, BOJ, etc.), the 1–2 day FRED lag vs going directly to each central bank's API is irrelevant for a macro dashboard updating weekly. The benefit of FRED as a single unified API with consistent formatting far outweighs the marginal lag.

The dashboard "Last Updated" display should show **two** things:
1. The date of the most recent **data point** in each series (data freshness)
2. The next **scheduled release** with a live countdown (see Section 5)

